Okay, so now lets test the wetland obligate plants seperately from the generalist and upland species. If the ditch effect is only a drying affect we should see a significant ditch effect on the wetland plants but no significant effect on the upland plants.

Initial Setup

Now draw a picutre of the wetland plant data.

First we will look at diversity using richness as our measure of diversity

Wow these data are going to be tricky. These are bound between zero and 1, and they appear to be zero inflated. There also is no meaningful denominator associated with the proportions so questionable as to wehther we can assume binomial error. So, I will attemtp to analyse them using a mixed model betaregression approach using glmmtmb. THis is a brand new tool solets see what happens?

wp1=glmmTMB(meanimp_sq~(Year_sc * Mowing * Fertilizer) + Ditch + (1|BLOCK/QUADRAT..), data=WRC_wetdat.2,ziformula = ~1, family=beta_family(link = "logit"))
wp2=glmmTMB(meanimp_sq~(Year_sc * Mowing * Fertilizer) + Ditch + (1|BLOCK/QUADRAT..), data=WRC_wetdat.2,ziformula = ~., family=beta_family(link = "logit"))
wp3=glmmTMB(meanimp_sq~(Year_sc * Mowing * Fertilizer) + Ditch + (1|BLOCK/QUADRAT..), data=WRC_wetdat.2,ziformula = ~(Year_sc * Mowing * Fertilizer) + Ditch, family=beta_family(link = "logit"))
wp4=glmmTMB(meanimp_sq~(Year_sc * Mowing * Fertilizer) + Ditch + (1|BLOCK/QUADRAT..), data=WRC_wetdat.2,ziformula = ~0, family=beta_family(link = "logit"))
